WeRateDogs Twitter Data Wrangling¶

Project Details¶

A complete assessment and cleaning of the entire dataset would require extraordinary effort, so it was necessary to assess only part of its problems and clean up the data obtained from 3 sources:

  1. Tweet archive of Twitter from @dog_rates, WeRateDogs is a Twitter account that rates the dogs of people with a humorous comment about the dog. These ratings almost always have a denominator of 10. What about the numerators? Almost always more than 10.11 / 10, etc.

  2. Tweet Image Predictions File Every image in the Twitter WeRateDogs archive has been processed by a neural network that can classify dog breeds. Results: A table full of the top three image predictions, plus each tweet ID, image URL, and image numbe

  3. Data through the Twitter API Since we have the tweet IDs from the WeRateDogs Twitter archive, we will be able to collect the number of retweets, the number of favorites, and any additional data you find interesting for all available tweets. The Twitter API requires users to be authorized to use it. This means that you need to create your own Twitter developer account before you can run your API request code.

Data wrangling:¶

  1. Gathering data
    • Direct
    • Through request
    • Twitter API
  2. Assessing data
  3. Cleaning data
  4. Visualizing and analyzing

Step 2. Assessing Data¶

After gathering all three pieces of data, assess them visually and programmatically for quality and tidiness issues. Detect and document at least eight (8) quality issues and two (2) tidiness issues in the "Accessing Data" section in the wrangle_act.ipynb Jupyter Notebook.

Quality Issues¶

Low quality data is commonly referred to as dirty data. Dirty data has issues with its content. Data that has issues with data content including:

  • Missing data
  • Invalid data
  • Inaccurate data
  • Inconsistent data

  • drop duplicated jpg_url
  • rename columns in clear names
  1. 'tweet_json' table:
  • id should be rename to tweet_id for further merging
  • id and id_str are the same

  • Create new column 'breed' from 4 merged 'doggo', 'floofer', 'pupper' and 'puppo' columns

Final step of Data Wrangling conssist from: define, code and test.

# copy of dataframe for twitter_archive_enhanced

df_clean = df.copy()

Quality issues(8)¶

Define:¶

  1. Convert to date type timestramp
  2. Drop missing values in tweet urls
  3. Rename columns to clear names
  4. Delete unnecesary columns
  5. Replace Invalid names from name Column with NaN
  6. Dropout p1_confidence less then 0,5 in image_prediction
  7. p1, p2 and p3 in df_pred has uppercase and lowcase ans should be Uppercase
  8. "name" column have invalid names: 'None', 'a', 'an'
  9. Merge all tables in one

Tidiness¶

There are three requirements for tidiness.

  • Each variable forms a column
  • Each observation forms a row
  • Each type of observational unit forms a table
  1. Make part of image_predictions as a be part of the twitter_archive table
  2. Create one table "rating" from rating_numerator and rating_denominator

# create another column for tweets that is not one of four stages
cover = ((df_clean['doggo'] == 'None') & (df_clean['floofer'] == 'None') 
        & (df_clean['pupper'] == 'None') & (df_clean['puppo'] == 'None'))

# we will make 5 values: 'doggo', 'floofer', 'pupper', 'puppo' and 'not_specified'
# for dogs without any kind.
df_clean['not_specified'] = np.where(cover, 'not_specified', 'None')
merge = set(['doggo', 'floofer', 'pupper', 'puppo', 'not_specified'])

df_clean = df_clean.melt(id_vars= set(df_clean.columns).difference(merge), 
                          value_vars= merge, 
                          var_name='dog_kind', 
                          value_name='value')
# remove extra rows an column
cover = df_clean['dog_kind'] == df_clean['value']
df_clean = df_clean[cover]
df_clean.drop(columns='value', inplace=True)
